Two-way partitioning
Another implementation is to use two indexes for partition. It speeds up the partition by working two-way simultaneously, both from lower bound toward right and from upper bound toward left, instead of traversing one-way through the sequence.
The gif below shows the complete process on [6, 5, 3, 1, 8, 7, 2, 4].


Take 3 as the pivot.
Let pointer lo start with number 6 and pointer hi start with number 4. Keep increasing lo until it comes to an element ≥ the pivot, and decreasing hi until it comes to an element 
Increase lo and decrease hi (both by 1), and repeat step 2 so that lo comes to 5 and hi comes to 1. Swap again.
Increase lo and decrease hi (both by 1) until they meet (at 3). The partition for pivot 3 ends. Apply the same operations on the left and right part of pivot 3.

A more general interpretation:

Init iii and jjj to be at the two ends of given array.
Take the first element as the pivot.
Perform partition, which is a loop with two inner-loops:
One that increases iii, until it comes to an element ≥ pivot.
The other that decreases jjj, until it comes to an element 


Check whether iii and jjj meet or overlap. If so, swap the elements.

Think of a sequence whose elements are all equal. In such case, each partition will return the middle element, thus recursion will happen logn\log nlogn times. For each level of recursion, it takes nnn times of comparison. The total comparison is nlognn \log nnlogn then. programming_pearls
